    "description": {
      "value": "<p><em>Biome: Underdark &amp; Caves</em></p>\\n<p>A leafy groundcover that resembles collard greens but in shades of charcoal gray and blood red. Death&rsquo;s Collard can be shredded and steeped in sacramental wine with garlic to produce a brew called Bloodwine. Though mildly poisonous to the living, Bloodwine tastes savory with a copper finish and is especially harmful to vampires and other undead, which have disadvantage on saving throws against its effects. When consumed, the poison remains in a living creature for up to 12 hours; any undead that feed on that creature or drink its blood are affected as if they had ingested Bloodwine themselves. An undead subjected to the poison must make a Constitution saving throw: on a failure it takes [[/roll 3d6]] radiant damage, or half as much on a success.</p>",
